   <abstract >Spanish composers María Rodrigo Bellido (1888-1967) and Emiliana Zubeldía e Inda (1888-1987) exhibit remarkable personal and professional parallels. Both were born the same year during the Bourbon Restoration in Spain, received world-class training abroad, and were accomplished concert pianists and published composers in an era when most Spanish women were illiterate. Still in their prime, they left Spain and lived the remainder of their lives in the Americas, having key roles in the establishment of collegiate music programs in Puerto Rico and Mexico, respectively. It is difficult to overestimate the quality of their work and significance of their achievements. Their music is endowed with rich individuality and reflects the synthesis of wider European musical trends, national and regional folk music, key mentors' and collaborators' influences, and their own unique compositional vision. Both were prolific vocal and instrumental composers, yet neither has received due recognition outside of Mexico and Spain. Very little of their work has been published, and the scores that do exist are often hard to locate and difficult to read. Additionally, the majority of the limited scholarly research published about their lives is written exclusively in Spanish, making it inaccessible to an English-speaking audience. This project represents an essential English-language biographical resource and a detailed analysis of twenty-five of Rodrigo and Zubeldía's art songs, with the object of providing greater awareness of and access to this body of work for students, teachers, and professional performers in classical voice. With over 41 million Spanish speakers in the United States and a growing demand for racial, cultural, and gender inclusivity, this treatise is an important addition to existing literature.</abstract>
